{{short description|The upper boundary of the stratosphere}}
{{Unreferenced|date=June 2009}}
The '''stratopause''' (formerly '''Mesopeak''') is the level of the [[Earth's atmosphere|atmosphere]] which is the boundary between two layers: the [[stratosphere]] and the [[mesosphere]]. In the stratosphere the [[temperature]] increases with [[altitude]], and the '''stratopause''' is the region where a maximum in the temperature occurs.
This atmospheric feature is not only associated with Earth: it occurs on any other [[planet]] or moon that has an [[celestial body's atmosphere|atmosphere]] as well<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://what-when-how.com/global-warming/stratopause-global-warming/|title=Stratopause (Global Warming)|website=what-when-how.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-05-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.actforlibraries.org/what-is-the-stratopause/|title=What is the Stratopause|work=Actforlibraries.org|access-date=2017-05-22|language=en-US}}</ref>.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.weather-climate.org.uk/02.php|title=Atmosphere {{!}} Troposphere {{!}} Stratosphere {{!}} Mesosphere {{!}} Thermosphere|website=www.weather-climate.org.uk|access-date=2017-05-22}}</ref>

On [[Earth]], the stratopause is {{convert|50|to(-)|55|km|mi}} high above the Earth's surface. The atmospheric [[pressure]] is around 1/1000 of the pressure at [[sea level]]. The temperature in the stratopause is -15 degrees Celsius (5 degrees Fahrenheit).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/science/stratopause|title=stratopause {{!}} meteorology|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2017-05-22|language=en}}</ref>

